2 SENATE BILL 977
1 Annotated Code of Maryland
2 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
3 Preamble
4 WHEREAS, The General Assembly of Maryland finds that the health, safety, and
5 well–being of Maryland’s children and young adults is essential to the long–term social,
6 educational, and economic success of the State; and
7 WHEREAS, A growing body of research demonstrates that excessive and
8 unregulated social media use is associated with increased risk to youth mental health,
9 social isolation, anxiety, depression, and disrupted development; and
10 WHEREAS, The State is currently engaged in litigation seeking restitution from
11 social media companies to address harms caused to children and young adults; and
12 WHEREAS, Afterschool programs, summer learning programs, mentoring
13 programs, and other community–based youth development initiatives provide
14 evidence–based opportunities for children and young adults to build positive peer and adult
15 relationships, engage in meaningful learning, participate in physical activity, and develop
16 critical social and emotional skills; and
17 WHEREAS, These programs offer safe, developmentally appropriate alternatives to
18 excessive screen time and help disrupt negative cycles of social media dependency by
19 fostering connection, belonging, and real–world engagement; and
20 WHEREAS, The State currently lacks a dedicated, sustainable funding mechanism
21 to support positive youth development programs operating outside of traditional school
22 hours, despite the demonstrated need for and impact of these programs; and
23 WHEREAS, It is the intent of the General Assembly to establish a Maryland Positive
24 Youth Development Fund to leverage legal settlement proceeds and other revenue sources
25 to prevent harm, promote youth well–being, and expand access to high–quality,
26 community–based youth development opportunities across the State; now, therefore,
27 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
28 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
29 Article – Education
30 7–455.
31 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
32 INDICATED.
33 (2) “COMMISSION” MEANS THE MARYLAND POSITIVE YOUTH

SENATE BILL 977 3
1 DEVELOPMENT COMMISSION.
2 (3) “ELIGIBLE ORGANIZATIONS” MEANS COMMUNITY–BASED
3 ORGANIZATIONS, STATEWIDE YOUTH–SERVING ORGANIZATIONS, LOCAL
4 GOVERNMENTS, AND SCHOOLS DELIVERING YOUTH PROGRAMS OUTSIDE REGULAR
5 SCHOOL HOURS.
6 (4) “FUND” MEANS THE MARYLAND POSITIVE YOUTH
7 DEVELOPMENT FUND.
8 (5) “POSITIVE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMMING” MEANS
9 STRUCTURED, DEVELOPMENTALLY APPROPRIATE PROGRAMS OR ACTIVITIES THAT:
10 (I) ARE GROUNDED IN EVIDENCE–BASED OR
11 EVIDENCE–INFORMED PRACTICES;
12 (II) INCLUDE CONSISTENT, ENGAGED ADULT MENTORS OR
13 YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PROFESSIONALS;
14 (III) ARE PROVIDED BEFORE SCHOOL, AFTER SCHOOL, DURING
15 SUMMER, OR AT OTHER TIMES OUTSIDE REGULAR SCHOOL HOURS; AND
16 (IV) INCLUDE PROGRAMMING DESIGNED TO SUPPORT FAMILY
17 ENGAGEMENT.
18 (6) “YOUTH” MEANS INDIVIDUALS FROM BIRTH THROUGH 25 YEARS.
19 (B) (1) THERE IS A MARYLAND POSITIVE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT
20 COMMISSION IN THE DEPARTMENT.
21 (2) THE COMMISSION CONSISTS OF THE FOLLOWING MEMBERS:
22 (I) THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT, OR THE
23 SUPERINTENDENT’S DESIGNEE;
24 (II) FOUR MEMBERS, APPOINTED BY THE GOVERNOR, WHO:
25 1. ARE AT LEAST 14 YEARS OLD AND UNDER THE AGE OF
26 25 YEARS AT THE TIME OF APPOINTMENT;
27 2. COLLECTIVELY REFLECT THE GEOGRAPHIC, RACIAL,
28 AND SOCIOECONOMIC DIVERSITY OF THE STATE; AND

4 SENATE BILL 977
1 3. HAVE PARTICIPATED IN OR HAVE BEEN IMPACTED BY
2 COMMUNITY–BASED YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS;
3 (III) ONE MEMBER WHO IS A PARENT OF A YOUTH WHO RESIDES
4 IN A RURAL JURISDICTION, APPOINTED BY THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT;
5 (IV) ONE MEMBER WHO IS A PARENT OF A YOUTH WHO RESIDES
6 IN AN URBAN JURISDICTION, APPOINTED BY THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT;
7 (V) ONE MEMBER, APPOINTED BY THE SECRETARY OF THE
8 GOVERNOR’S OFFICE FOR CHILDREN;
9 (VI) ONE MEMBER, APPOINTED BY THE ATTORNEY GENERAL;
10 (VII) ONE MEMBER, APPOINTED BY THE SECRETARY OF
11 JUVENILE SERVICES;
12 (VIII) ONE MEMBER, APPOINTED BY THE SECRETARY OF HUMAN
13 SERVICES;
14 (IX) ONE MEMBER, APPOINTED BY THE SECRETARY OF HEALTH;
15 (X) ONE MEMBER WHO IS A LICENSED PSYCHOLOGIST OR
16 BEHAVIORAL HEALTH PROFESSIONAL WITH EXPERTISE IN ADOLESCENT MENTAL
17 HEALTH AND THE IMPACT OF SOCIAL MEDIA USE, APPOINTED BY THE GOVERNOR;
18 (XI) ONE MEMBER, APPOINTED BY THE COMPTROLLER;
19 (XII) TWO MEMBERS REPRESENTING THE LOCAL MANAGEMENT
20 BOARDS, APPOINTED BY THE COCHAIRS OF THE MARYLAND ASSOCIATION OF
21 LOCAL MANAGEMENT BOARDS; AND
22 (XIII) THE FOLLOWING MEMBERS, WHO SHALL ACT IN AN
23 ADVISORY CAPACITY:
24 1. ONE MEMBER OF THE HOUSE OF DELEGATES,
25 APPOINTED BY THE SPEAKER OF THE HOUSE;
26 2. ONE MEMBER OF THE SENATE OF MARYLAND,
27 APPOINTED BY THE PRESIDENT OF THE SENATE;
28 3. TWO MEMBERS FROM DIFFERENT GEOGRAPHIC
29 REGIONS OF THE STATE WHO REPRESENT STATEWIDE YOUTH–SERVING

SENATE BILL 977 5
1 ORGANIZATIONS, APPOINTED BY STATEWIDE YOUTH–SERVING ORGANIZATIONS;
2 AND
3 4. ONE MEMBER REPRESENTING A STATEWIDE
4 AFTERSCHOOL NETWORK, APPOINTED BY THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT.
5 (3) (I) THE TERM OF A MEMBER IS 2 YEARS.
6 (II) AT THE END OF A TERM, A MEMBER CONTINUES TO SERVE
7 UNTIL A SUCCESSOR IS APPOINTED.
8 (III) A MEMBER WHO IS APPOINTED AFTER A TERM HAS BEGUN
9 SERVES ONLY FOR THE REST OF THE TERM AND UNTIL A SUCCESSOR IS APPOINTED.
10 (IV) THE TERMS SHALL BE STAGGERED WITH 50% OF THE
11 INITIAL MEMBERS SERVING 2 YEARS AND THE REMAINING INITIAL MEMBERS
12 SERVING 3 YEARS.
13 (4) THE COMMISSION SHALL BE COCHAIRED BY:
14 (I) THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT; AND
15 (II) A MEMBER APPOINTED UNDER PARAGRAPH (2)(II) OF THIS
16 SUBSECTION WHO HAS BEEN SELECTED BY OTHER MEMBERS APPOINTED UNDER
17 PARAGRAPH (2)(II) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
18 (5) (I) THE COMMISSION SHALL MEET AT LEAST TWO TIMES PER
19 CALENDAR YEAR.
20 (II) THE COMMISSION IS SUBJECT TO THE OPEN MEETINGS
21 ACT.
22 (III) A MAJORITY OF THE VOTING MEMBERS OF THE
23 COMMISSION SHALL CONSTITUTE A QUORUM FOR THE TRANSACTION OF BUSINESS.
24 (IV) A MEMBER OF THE COMMISSION:
25 1. MAY NOT RECEIVE COMPENSATION AS A MEMBER OF
26 THE COMMISSION; BUT
27 2. IS ENTITLED TO REIMBURSEMENT FOR EXPENSES
28 UNDER THE STANDARD STATE TRAVEL REGULATIONS, AS PROVIDED IN THE STATE
29 BUDGET.

6 SENATE BILL 977
1 (C) THE COMMISSION SHALL:
2 (1) ESTABLISH A GRANT APPLICATION AND REVIEW PROCESS FOR
3 ELIGIBLE ORGANIZATIONS;
4 (2) MAKE GRANT AWARDS TO SUPPORT POSITIVE YOUTH
5 DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMMING ACROSS THE STATE;
6 (3) MONITOR AND EVALUATE ELIGIBLE ORGANIZATIONS THAT HAVE
7 RECEIVED A GRANT;
8 (4) ENSURE THE QUALITY AND POSITIVE OUTCOMES OF A GRANT;
9 AND
10 (5) ENSURE MEANINGFUL ENGAGEMENT OF YOUTH IN ALL ASPECTS
11 OF THE COMMISSION’S WORK, INCLUDING FUNDING PRIORITIES, GRANT REVIEW,
12 AND EVALUATION OF GRANTS.
13 (D) (1) THERE IS A MARYLAND POSITIVE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT FUND.
14 (2) THE PURPOSE OF THE FUND IS TO PROVIDE GRANTS TO ELIGIBLE
15 ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROVIDE POSITIVE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMMING
16 TO YOUTHS.
17 (3) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADMINISTER THE FUND.
18 (4) (I) THE FUND IS A SPECIAL, NONLAPSING FUND THAT IS NOT
19 SUBJECT TO § 7–302 OF THE STATE FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT ARTICLE.
20 (II) THE STATE TREASURER SHALL HOLD THE FUND
21 SEPARATELY, AND THE COMPTROLLER SHALL ACCOUNT FOR THE FUND.
22 (5) THE FUND CONSISTS OF:
23 (I) ALL REVENUES CONSISTING OF FUNDS RECEIVED BY THE
24 STATE FROM ANY SOURCE RESULTING, DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY, FROM ANY
25 JUDGMENT AGAINST OR SETTLEMENT WITH SOCIAL MEDIA COMPANIES FOUND TO
26 HAVE HARMED YOUTH;
27 (II) MONEY APPROPRIATED IN THE STATE BUDGET TO THE
28 FUND;

SENATE BILL 977 7
1 (III) INTEREST EARNINGS; AND
2 (IV) ANY OTHER MONEY FROM ANY OTHER SOURCE ACCEPTED
3 FOR THE BENEFIT OF THE FUND.
4 (6) THE FUND MAY BE USED ONLY AS FOLLOWS:
5 (I) UP TO 10% OF THE FUNDS FOR THE ADMINISTRATIVE COSTS
6 OF THE OFFICE OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL FOR LITIGATION AGAINST SOCIAL
7 MEDIA COMPANIES;
8 (II) UP TO 10% OF THE FUNDS FOR THE ADMINISTRATION OF
9 THE COMMISSION AND GRANTS AUTHORIZED BY THE COMMISSION, INCLUDING
10 TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND CAPACITY–BUILDING SUPPORT FOR ELIGIBLE
11 ORGANIZATIONS; AND
12 (III) THE REMAINING FUNDS FOR GRANTS TO ELIGIBLE
13 ORGANIZATIONS UNDER SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION.
14 (7) (I) THE STATE TREASURER SHALL INVEST THE MONEY OF THE
15 FUND IN THE SAME MANNER AS OTHER STATE MONEY MAY BE INVESTED.
16 (II) ANY INTEREST EARNINGS OF THE FUND SHALL BE
17 CREDITED TO THE FUND.
18 (8) EXPENDITURES FROM THE FUND MAY BE MADE ONLY IN
19 ACCORDANCE WITH THE STATE BUDGET.
20 (9) MONEY EXPENDED FROM THE FUND FOR GRANTS TO ELIGIBLE
21 ORGANIZATIONS IS SUPPLEMENTAL TO AND IS NOT INTENDED TO TAKE THE PLACE
22 OF FUNDING THAT OTHERWISE WOULD BE APPROPRIATED FOR PROVIDING
23 POSITIVE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMMING TO YOUTHS.
24 (E) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1 EACH YEAR, THE COMMISSION SHALL
25 REPORT TO THE GOVERNOR AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
26 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY ON:
27 (1) REVENUES DEPOSITED INTO THE FUND;
28 (2) GRANTS AWARDED AND POPULATIONS SERVED BY THE GRANTS;
29 (3) THE OUTCOMES AND IMPACTS OF THE GRANTS; AND

8 SENATE BILL 977
1 (4) RECOMMENDATIONS FOR POLICY AND FUNDING CHANGES TO
2 ADVANCE POSITIVE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT IN THE STATE.
3 (F) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS NECESSARY TO CARRY
4 OUT THIS SECTION.
5 Article – State Finance and Procurement
6 6–226.
7 (a) (2) (i) This paragraph does not apply in fiscal years 2024 through 2028.
8 (ii) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, and unless
9 inconsistent with a federal law, grant agreement, or other federal requirement or with the
10 terms of a gift or settlement agreement, net interest on all State money allocated by the
11 State Treasurer under this section to special funds or accounts, and otherwise entitled to
12 receive interest earnings, as accounted for by the Comptroller, shall accrue to the General
13 Fund of the State.
14 (iii) The provisions of subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph do not
15 apply to the following funds:
16 212. the Department of Social and Economic Mobility Special
17 Fund; [and]
18 213. the Population Health Improvement Fund; AND
19 214. THE MARYLAND POSITIVE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT
20 FUND.
21 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
22 (a) Section 1 of this Act is contingent on the State receiving funds resulting from
23 the execution of a final settlement agreement, judgment, or bankruptcy proceeding against
24 a social media company related to harm against children.
25 (b) The Attorney General shall provide written notice of the State receiving funds
26 resulting from the execution of a final settlement agreement, judgment, or bankruptcy
27 proceeding to the Department of Legislative Services, 90 State Circle, Annapolis, MD
28 21401.
29 (c) Section 1 of this Act, with no further action required by the General Assembly,
30 shall be null and void if, on or before June 30, 2030, the Department of Legislative Services
31 has not received notice from the Attorney General under subsection (b) of this section.
32 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, except as provided in Section

SENATE BILL 977 9
1 2 of this Act, this Act shall take effect July 1, 2026.

